{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a4e0fe6c-ad8b-4cc8-ad2c-f40bc2d7e0ef","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically captures crash reports — no `createdump` needed.\n\n**Look here for crash reports:**\n\n- **User crashes:** `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n- **System crashes:** `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n\nFiles will be `.ips` (JSON) or `.crash` (plain text) format, named after your process.\n\n**Quick find:**\n```bash\nls -lt ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/ | head\n```\n\n**To get a core dump instead**, enable them before running:\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited\n```\nCore files land in `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\nThe `.ips` crash log usually has enough info (backtrace, signal, registers) to start triaging. If you have an `.ips` file with .NET runtime frames, I can help symbolicate it using the **apple-crash-symbolication** skill.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6480e68c-2301-42ac-95f1-469637b72d8f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS when `createdump` isn't available. This is a diagnostic/knowledge question — I don't need to search a codebase for this.\n\nOn macOS, when an app crashes, the system automatically generates crash reports (`.ips` files) in specific locations. Let me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":328,"requestId":"4181:3BA809:62C8CC3:6C0711F:69F16373"},"id":"8770375b-6e1b-40ef-b910-f8d80e963409","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:48:46.792Z","parentId":"d54d2355-bd13-4b5d-a3b3-030984881556"}
